// Researched content for mexico-puerto-vallarta. Written per property.
module.exports = {
  'velas-vallarta': {
    activities: `Velas Vallarta sits in the Marina Vallarta district, and its centerpiece is a long lazy river winding past a swim-up bar and heated pool, backed by tennis courts and a spa. All-suite rooms suit families staying a week or more. Off-site, the golf courses and yacht marina are a short walk, while boat trips from the marina reach the Marietas Islands' hidden beach and Los Arcos for snorkeling; December through March adds humpback whale watching in Banderas Bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Velas Vallarta is an all-suite, family-oriented resort in Marina Vallarta, minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport and the cruise pier. Service and cleanliness are standout marks, both above 9, and the resort's 9.3 overall reflects consistently strong rooms and value; the beach and pool scores are softer, since this marina waterfront is calmer and more built-up than the open beaches further north. It suits multi-generational groups wanting suite-style space over a big swimmable beach. December through April brings the driest, most temperate weather and the winter whale-watching season in Banderas Bay.`,
  },
  'villa-premiere-boutique-hotel': {
    activities: `This 80-suite boutique hotel sits directly on Puerto Vallarta's main beach, a 10-minute walk from the Malecón boardwalk and its bronze sculptures. Days center on two oceanfront pools, a full spa with daily beach yoga, and butler service rather than large-scale programming. From here, guests book Zona Romántica's restaurants and galleries, snorkeling trips to Los Arcos, and December–March whale watching or Marietas Islands boat excursions departing Banderas Bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Villa Premiere is an adults-only boutique property in downtown Puerto Vallarta, on the Jalisco side of Banderas Bay, reached from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport in about 15 minutes. Its ratings are uniformly high — service, cleanliness, and rooms all above 9 — reflecting an intimate, all-suite format rather than a mega-resort. The beach score is its softest mark, since this stretch of city beach is narrower and busier than Nuevo Vallarta's or Punta de Mita's. It suits couples wanting a quiet, walkable base near downtown over sprawling resort grounds. Winter and spring bring the driest weather and calmer bay waters.`,
  },
  'villa-la-estancia-beach-resort-and-spa-riviera-nayarit': {
    activities: `Villa La Estancia sits on the wide Flamingos beach corridor of Riviera Nayarit, with a swim-up bar, heated pools, tennis, and a spa built around the resort's all-suite towers. A kids' club and diving program round out on-site options. Nearby, Flamingos Golf Club, the marina town of La Cruz de Huanacaxtle, and boat excursions to the Marietas Islands and Punta de Mita's surf breaks are all within a short drive.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This all-suite resort sits on the Flamingos stretch of Riviera Nayarit, on the Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, about 45 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Ratings are strong across the board — a 9.4 overall with rooms, cleanliness, and service all above 9 — and the beach, at 6.8, is one of the better marks among nearby properties, wider and calmer than the Puerto Vallarta city beaches. It's built for families wanting suite-sized space rather than standard hotel rooms. Winter through spring is the dry season here, and December–March overlaps with humpback whale season offshore.`,
  },
  'hotel-mousai-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Hotel Mousai is a cliffside, adults-only property in the Conchas Chinas hills south of downtown, built around four pools, a rooftop lounge, and Japanese and international restaurants rather than daytime programming. Suites include private plunge pools. Guests head down to Garza Blanca and Playa Esmeralda beaches for swimming, and book snorkeling at nearby Los Arcos, Sierra Madre canopy tours, or December–March whale-watching trips from the Puerto Vallarta marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Mousai sits on the Conchas Chinas hillside just south of central Puerto Vallarta, on the Jalisco side of the bay, about 25 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. It carries some of the higher marks in our database for rooms, service, and cleanliness, all above 9.5, reflecting its Five Diamond, all-suite positioning; the beach score is soft, since the hillside setting means no direct sandy beach at the hotel itself. This is a couples' retreat built for design and quiet rather than a beach-club vacation. Winter and spring bring the driest weather and the best conditions for the coastal excursions the hotel arranges.`,
  },
  'garza-blanca-preserve-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Garza Blanca occupies a jungle-backed stretch of coastline south of downtown Puerto Vallarta, with terraced infinity pools, an adult-only pool, a large spa, and daily yoga built into the grounds. A kids' club runs alongside, and the resort books snorkeling and diving trips to nearby Los Arcos. The Sierra Madre foothills just inland offer zip-line canopy tours, and December through March brings humpback whale watching by boat from the marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Garza Blanca sits on Puerto Vallarta's south shore, between downtown and Mismaloya, about 25 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Rooms, cleanliness, and food all score above 8.7, and the pool complex is one of its stronger marks at 8.7; the beach here is soft at 5.5, since this jungle coastline is rockier than the open sand further north. It works for both families and couples, with an adult-only pool separating the two. Pets are welcome, a rarity locally. December through April is the dry season and the best window for the whale-watching and snorkeling trips the resort arranges.`,
  },
  'marival-distinct-residences-and-spa': {
    activities: `Marival Distinct is built around multi-bedroom suites and villas for large families, with a lazy river, water feature, and dedicated kids' waterpark alongside a teen club, tennis, and a full spa. Fishing charters and evening entertainment fill out the schedule. The resort's private beach club fronts Nuevo Vallarta's long sand, and Marietas Islands boat trips, Sierra Madre canopy tours, and December–March whale watching are common day excursions from here.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Marival Distinct sits in Nuevo Vallarta on the Riviera Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, about 30 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. It's built for large multi-generational groups, with residence-style suites sleeping up to 11 and rooms, service, and cleanliness all scoring above 9.4. The beach mark of 6 is middling for the area — solid but not the region's best — while value and the 9.4 overall are among the stronger scores here. This is a family property through and through, with limited appeal for couples seeking quiet. Dry season runs roughly November through April, the easiest stretch for beach days and boat excursions.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-palace-pacifico': {
    activities: `Riu Palace Pacífico is an adults-only, all-inclusive property on the Flamingos stretch of Riviera Nayarit, with the reliably large Riu buffet and à la carte restaurant rotation, a swim-up bar, and nightly entertainment shared with neighboring Riu properties. The beach here is one of the better ones on this part of the bay. Off-site, day trips reach the Marietas Islands' hidden beach, Punta de Mita's surf breaks, and December–March whale-watching tours out of Banderas Bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Riu Palace sits on Flamingos beach in Riviera Nayarit, on the Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, roughly 25 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Cleanliness (9.3) and service (9) are its strongest marks, standard for the Riu chain, while food and atmosphere sit in the mid-7s — reliable rather than exceptional, in keeping with the brand's high-volume format. At 6.8, the beach is a genuine asset compared with several Puerto Vallarta city properties. As an adults-only Riu, it draws couples and groups over families, who are steered to sister property Hotel Riu Vallarta nearby. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'hyatt-ziva-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Hyatt Ziva Puerto Vallarta sits on one of the coast's few private beaches, in the southern hotel zone near Mismaloya, with a kids' club, swim-up bar, tennis, and an adults-only pool alongside the main family pool. Fishing charters and a dive program are bookable on-site. Los Arcos snorkeling is a short trip from here, and the resort also arranges Sierra Madre canopy tours and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hyatt Ziva Puerto Vallarta sits in the Zona Hotelera Sur near Mismaloya, on the Jalisco side of Banderas Bay, about 30 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Location (9) and service (9.1) are its top marks, and the beach, at 7.5, stands out — the resort holds one of the only private beaches on this stretch of coast, genuinely better than most Puerto Vallarta hotel-zone properties. Food and atmosphere are more middling, in the high-7s. It's built for families, with an adults-only pool section for couples traveling together. Winter through spring is the dry season and prime time for the bay's whale-watching boats.`,
  },
  'marriott-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `The Marriott Puerto Vallarta sits in the Marina Vallarta golf and yacht-marina district, with a kids' club, waterpark section for younger children, tennis, watersports rentals, and bicycles available on property. The marina's restaurants and the adjacent 18-hole course are a short walk. Guests head out from here for Marietas Islands boat trips, Los Arcos snorkeling, and December–March whale watching, all departing the nearby marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Marriott sits in Marina Vallarta, Puerto Vallarta's golf-and-yacht district on the Jalisco side of the bay, a few minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Service (9.2) and cleanliness (9.1) are strong, and the resort scores a solid 9.1 overall; the beach is its clear weak point at 5, reflecting the narrower, more built-up sand typical of the marina area rather than open coastline. It's a family property with enough golf and marina activity to fill non-beach days easily. Book it for the marina setting and brand consistency rather than for standout sand. Dry season runs November through April.`,
  },
  'hard-rock-hotel-vallarta': {
    activities: `Hard Rock Hotel Vallarta leans into its music branding with a rock spa, teen club, nightclub, and arcade alongside a full waterpark-style pool with slides for younger kids. Fishing charters and evening entertainment round out the on-site list. In Nuevo Vallarta, it's a short drive to the marina and golf courses, and to boat excursions reaching the Marietas Islands, Punta de Mita, and December–March whale-watching grounds in Banderas Bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hard Rock Hotel Vallarta sits in Nuevo Vallarta on the Riviera Nayarit side of the bay, about 30 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. It scores well across the board — a 9.1 overall with service, cleanliness, and location all above 8.8 — and the beach, at 6.8, holds up better than most Puerto Vallarta city properties. Food and atmosphere sit in the mid-7s, solid without being exceptional. This is a family resort with teen and kids' clubs plus a nightclub for the adults, so it runs lively rather than quiet. November through April is the dry season for beach days and boat trips.`,
  },
  'family-selection-at-grand-palladium-vallarta-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `This is the family wing of the Grand Palladium Vallarta complex on the Riviera Nayarit coast near Punta de Mita, with a kids' club, nightclub, tennis, and evening entertainment shared across the property's pools and beach frontage. The location puts Punta de Mita's surf breaks and the Marietas Islands boat excursions within easy reach, along with December–March whale watching and Sierra Madre canopy-zipline tours inland.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Family Selection sits within the Grand Palladium Vallarta complex on the Riviera Nayarit coast near Punta de Mita, about 45 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. This family-designated section carries a 9.2 overall with location and service both above 8.5; the beach score of 5.5 is soft for this generally beach-strong part of the coast, worth noting if sand is a priority. It suits families wanting resort-complex scale — multiple pools, restaurants, and entertainment shared across the wider Palladium property. The adjacent main Grand Palladium building serves couples and other non-family guests. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'iberostar-selection-playa-mita': {
    activities: `Iberostar Selection Playa Mita sits on the Punta de Mita peninsula, with a golf course nearby, a dive program, teen club, and waterpark section for younger kids alongside the standard Iberostar buffet and entertainment rotation. This end of Banderas Bay is the launch point for boat trips to the Marietas Islands' hidden beach, surfing at nearby breaks, and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Iberostar sits at Punta de Mita, the peninsula at the north end of Banderas Bay in Riviera Nayarit, roughly 45 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Cleanliness (9.2) and service (9) are its top marks; food and atmosphere sit closer to 7, average for the brand's all-inclusive format. The 6.3 beach score is respectable but not exceptional for this part of the coast, which has some of the region's better sand. It's a family resort with teen and kids' clubs. Punta de Mita's position makes it the most convenient base for Marietas Islands trips. Dry season runs November through April.`,
  },
  'secrets-vallarta-bay-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Secrets Vallarta Bay is an adults-only, unlimited-luxury property near Marina Vallarta, built around a heated pool, swim-up bar, spa, and nightclub rather than family programming. Its restaurants don't require reservations, unusual for the brand. From here, guests reach the Malecón and Zona Romántica for dining, and book Los Arcos snorkeling, Sierra Madre zip-lining, and December–March whale-watching trips departing the nearby marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Secrets Vallarta Bay sits near Marina Vallarta on the Jalisco side of Banderas Bay, a short drive from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Rooms and cleanliness both score above 9, and service is close behind at 9.2; the beach, at 6, is middling — usable but not the property's headline feature. As an adults-only, all-inclusive resort it's built for couples and groups without kids. Sister property Dreams Vallarta Bay next door handles families. Winter through spring is the dry season, and the same months bring humpback whales into the bay, visible on boat trips arranged through the resort.`,
  },
  'sunset-plaza-beach-resort': {
    activities: `Sunset Plaza is a mid-size, family-friendly beachfront hotel in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone, with an adult-only pool alongside the main pool, tennis, horseback riding, and a spa. A kids' club runs during the day. The Malecón and Zona Romántica are a short taxi ride for dining and nightlife, and the resort books Los Arcos snorkeling trips and December–March whale-watching excursions from the nearby marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sunset Plaza sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, close to Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Rooms (9.2), cleanliness (9.3), and value (9) are its strongest marks; the beach is a softer 5.8, typical of this stretch of city coastline compared with Nuevo Vallarta or Punta de Mita's wider sand. It's a family property with an adult pool section for couples traveling together. Book it for value and room quality rather than for beachfront standout. November through April is Puerto Vallarta's dry season, with the calmest seas and best whale-watching conditions.`,
  },
  'secrets-bahia-mita-surf-and-spa-resort': {
    activities: `Secrets Bahía Mita is an adults-only resort at Punta de Mita named for the surf breaks right offshore, with a heated pool, swim-up bar, spa, and nightclub on-site, and restaurants that skip reservations. Guests here surf or take lessons at the point breaks nearby, book snorkeling and boat trips to the Marietas Islands' hidden beach, and watch for humpback whales on the water December through March.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Secrets resort sits at Punta de Mita, the surf-oriented point at the north end of Banderas Bay in Riviera Nayarit, about 45 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Sleep quality (9) and cleanliness (9.3) are among its stronger marks; the beach, at 5, is the softest score, since Punta de Mita's coastline here is more about surf breaks and rock points than swimming sand. It's an adults-only, pet-friendly property built for couples drawn to the surf culture rather than a classic beach vacation. Punta de Mita is the closest base to the Marietas Islands. Winter is both surf season's shoulder and the dry season.`,
  },
  'fiesta-americana-puerto-vallarta-and-spa': {
    activities: `Fiesta Americana Puerto Vallarta is known locally for its distinctive palapa-roofed lobby, one of the hotel zone's landmarks. On-site there's a kids' and teen club, heated pool, swim-up bar, and spa. The Malecón boardwalk and its sculpture walk are an easy walk south, while snorkeling at Los Arcos, Sierra Madre canopy tours, and December–March whale-watching trips are common excursions arranged through the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Fiesta Americana sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, close to Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport and a short drive from downtown. Location (8.9) and cleanliness (9.1) are strong marks; the beach sits at a moderate 6, and pool and atmosphere are more middling in the high 6s. It's a family resort with kids' and teen clubs. The palapa-topped lobby is the property's best-known architectural feature and a genuine local landmark, not just a marketing line. Winter and spring bring the driest weather and the best whale-watching conditions in the bay.`,
  },
  'hilton-vallarta-riviera-resort': {
    activities: `Hilton Vallarta Riviera combines kids' and teen clubs with an adult-only pool, snorkeling and watersports rentals, yoga classes, and a nightclub for evenings. Its location in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone puts the Malecón and Zona Romántica within easy reach for dining out. The resort also books Los Arcos snorkeling excursions, Sierra Madre zip-line tours, and December–March whale-watching trips into Banderas Bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Hilton sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, a short drive from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Rooms (9) and sleep quality (8.8) stand out; food and atmosphere are more middling in the 7-range, and the beach, at 6, is respectable without being a headline feature. It's a family property with an adult pool for couples and pets welcome, unusual for the area. This works well as a comfortable, brand-reliable base for exploring downtown rather than as a destination beach in itself. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'armony-marival-resort-and-spa-punta-de-mita': {
    activities: `Armony Marival is a smaller, adults-only property at Punta de Mita with a heated pool, swim-up bar, spa, and daily yoga rather than large-scale entertainment. Hiking trails and snorkeling gear are available on-site. Its position on the peninsula makes it a convenient base for surfing nearby breaks, boat trips to the Marietas Islands' hidden beach, and December–March whale-watching excursions into Banderas Bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Armony Marival sits at Punta de Mita, the peninsula at the northern tip of Banderas Bay in Riviera Nayarit, about 45 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Cleanliness (9.3) and room quality (9.1) are strong marks, and the beach, at 6.8, is one of the better scores among nearby properties. Food and atmosphere sit closer to 7.5, solid rather than exceptional. As a smaller, adults-only resort it suits couples wanting quiet over big-resort scale. Punta de Mita's position makes it a natural jumping-off point for Marietas Islands trips. Dry season runs November through April.`,
  },
  'sheraton-buganvilias-resort-and-convention-center': {
    activities: `Sheraton Buganvilias is a large, walkable-to-downtown resort with a convention center attached, plus a kids' club, tennis, horseback riding, and a spa. Its hotel-zone location puts the Malecón boardwalk within walking distance for evenings out in the Zona Romántica. The resort also arranges Los Arcos snorkeling trips, Sierra Madre canopy tours, and December–March whale-watching excursions departing nearby.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sheraton Buganvilias sits at the edge of downtown Puerto Vallarta on the Jalisco side of the bay, within walking distance of the Malecón and close to Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport — rooms here are capped at three guests. Location (8.6) is solid, though the beach, at 4.8, is the property's weakest mark, narrower and more exposed than the sand further from downtown. It's a family hotel that also hosts conferences, so expect a business-and-leisure mix rather than a purely resort atmosphere. Its downtown-adjacent position is the real draw. November through April is the dry season for exploring on foot.`,
  },
  'decameron-la-marina-guayabitos': {
    activities: `Decameron La Marina sits in Rincón de Guayabitos, a quieter family beach town well north of Puerto Vallarta on a sheltered bay. Days here center on the beach and buffet dining rather than extensive facilities. The town's calm, shallow water suits young children, and it's a base for exploring nearby coastal islets by boat, and, in winter, whale sightings further offshore.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Decameron sits in Rincón de Guayabitos, a low-key Nayarit beach town roughly 90 minutes north of Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport, well beyond the Nuevo Vallarta corridor. Location (8.5) and cleanliness (8.6) are its better marks; food (6.1) and pool (5.5) are the weakest, reflecting a simpler, budget all-inclusive format from the Colombian Decameron chain rather than a full-service resort. It suits families looking for an inexpensive, calm-water beach town over resort amenities. Guayabitos' sheltered bay makes it a popular choice for young children. Winter is the driest, most comfortable season for this stretch of coast.`,
  },
  'delta-hotels-by-marriott-riviera-nayarit': {
    activities: `This Delta by Marriott sits in La Cruz de Huanacaxtle, Riviera Nayarit's marina town, with a lazy river, adult-only pool, and spa on-site rather than a beach club. La Cruz's Sunday market and marina restaurants are a short walk, and the resort books sportfishing charters, Marietas Islands boat trips, and December–March whale-watching excursions departing the marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This property sits in La Cruz de Huanacaxtle, the marina town on the Riviera Nayarit coast, about 40 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Rooms (9) and cleanliness (9.1) are genuinely strong; the beach score of 3 is the weakest in this stretch of coast, and honestly so — La Cruz is built around its marina and sportfishing fleet rather than a swimming beach. Book it for the marina setting, fishing charters, and the town's Sunday organic market, not for sand. It suits couples and families equally, with an adult pool available. November through April is the dry season and peak sailfish and marlin season offshore.`,
  },
  'villa-del-palmar-flamingos-beach-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Villa del Palmar Flamingos sits on the Flamingos stretch of Riviera Nayarit, with a kids' club, heated pool, spa, and evening entertainment built around its all-suite towers. The adjacent Flamingos Golf Club is a short walk for golfers. Boat trips from nearby marinas reach the Marietas Islands' hidden beach and Punta de Mita's surf breaks, and December through March brings humpback whales into the bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Villa del Palmar sits on Flamingos beach in Riviera Nayarit, on the Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, about 30 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Cleanliness (9.2) and value (8.8) stand out, and the beach, at 6.8, is a genuine strength relative to Puerto Vallarta's city properties. Food and pool sit closer to 7, solid without being exceptional. It's an all-suite, family-oriented resort suited to groups wanting more space than a standard hotel room. The neighboring golf course adds a non-beach option. Dry season runs November through April, overlapping with winter whale watching.`,
  },
  'dreams-vallarta-bay-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Dreams Vallarta Bay is the family sibling to Secrets Vallarta Bay near Marina Vallarta, with a waterpark-style kids' pool, teen club, dive program, tennis, and a nightclub, plus an adult-only pool section. Its restaurants skip reservations. From here, guests reach the Malecón for evenings out, and book Los Arcos snorkeling, Sierra Madre zip-lining, and December–March whale-watching trips departing the nearby marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Dreams Vallarta Bay sits near Marina Vallarta on the Jalisco side of Banderas Bay, a short drive from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Cleanliness (9) and service (9) are consistent strengths, while the beach, at 6, and atmosphere, at 7.1, sit closer to the middle of the pack. As a family-oriented, unlimited-luxury resort it offers kids' and teen clubs plus an adult pool for couples traveling together. Sister property Secrets Vallarta Bay next door is adults-only for those wanting a childfree stay. Winter through spring is the dry season and the best window for whale-watching boats out of the marina.`,
  },
  'decameron-isla-coral-guayabitos': {
    activities: `Decameron Isla Coral is another Rincón de Guayabitos property on the same sheltered northern Nayarit bay, with straightforward beach and buffet-based days rather than extensive facilities. The calm water suits families with young kids, and the town is a base for exploring nearby coastal islets by boat, fishing trips, and winter whale sightings further out in the bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Decameron sits in Rincón de Guayabitos, roughly 90 minutes north of Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport, on a quieter stretch of the Nayarit coast well beyond the Nuevo Vallarta resort corridor. The beach (6.5) and location (8.2) are its better marks, while food (6.2) and pool (5.5) are the weakest — a simple, budget all-inclusive format rather than a full-service resort. It's a family property suited to travelers prioritizing an inexpensive, calm beach town over amenities. Guayabitos' protected bay makes it popular with families of young children. Winter offers the driest, calmest conditions.`,
  },
  'marival-emotions-resort-and-suites-riviera-nayarit': {
    activities: `Marival Emotions, the more moderately priced sibling to Marival Distinct, packs in a waterpark for younger kids, arcade, teen club, nightclub, and a dive program around its Nuevo Vallarta pools. Fishing charters and tennis round out the on-site list. Off-property, Marietas Islands boat trips, Sierra Madre canopy tours, and December–March whale-watching excursions are typical day trips from this stretch of Riviera Nayarit.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Marival Emotions sits in Nuevo Vallarta on the Riviera Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, about 30 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. The beach, at 6.8, holds up well against nearby competitors, though rooms (8) and value (8.3) are comparatively soft next to sister property Marival Distinct, reflecting its positioning as the more affordable, high-energy option in the same family. It's built for families with kids of all ages, heavy on organized activity and nightlife rather than quiet. November through April is the dry season, the easiest stretch for beach days and boat excursions to the Marietas Islands.`,
  },
  'the-westin-playa-vallarta': {
    activities: `The Westin Playa Vallarta's signature feature is its FlowRider surf simulator, unusual for the area, alongside a heated pool, swim-up bar, tennis, and kids' club. Pets are welcome. The hotel zone location puts the Malecón and Zona Romántica within reach for dinners out, and the resort books Los Arcos snorkeling trips, Sierra Madre zip-lining, and December–March whale-watching excursions in Banderas Bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Westin sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, close to Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Rooms (8.9) and service (8.9) are solid; the beach is a softer 5, more typical of this developed stretch of shoreline than the open sand north of the bay. Its FlowRider is a genuine differentiator worth noting for teens and active families. It's a family resort with pets allowed, unusual locally. Book it for the surf-simulator novelty and brand reliability rather than beachfront standout. November through April brings the driest weather.`,
  },
  'grand-palladium-vallarta-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `The main Grand Palladium Vallarta building sits on the Riviera Nayarit coast near Punta de Mita, with an adult-only pool, dive program, tennis, nightclub, and evening entertainment shared with its Family Selection wing next door. Fishing charters are bookable on-site. Punta de Mita's surf breaks, the Marietas Islands boat excursions, and December–March whale-watching trips are all easy day excursions from here.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Grand Palladium sits near Punta de Mita on the Riviera Nayarit coast, about 45 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport, on 300 meters of private beach. Ratings run lower here than at its Family Selection sibling — an 8.4 overall with food (6.8) and pool (6.5) the softer marks — while location and cleanliness hold up reasonably at 7.9–8.4. It's a large, garden-set complex with an adult pool alongside family areas. Consider it for the beachfront and Punta de Mita access more than for standout dining. November through April is the region's dry season.`,
  },
  'occidental-nuevo-vallarta': {
    activities: `Occidental Nuevo Vallarta sits on the longest stretch of beach in the Nuevo Vallarta corridor, with a dive program, adult-only pool, tennis, fishing charters, and a nightclub on-site. Vallarta Adventures' excursion base and the Nayar Vidanta golf course are both nearby. Guests here also book Marietas Islands boat trips, Sierra Madre canopy tours, and December–March whale-watching excursions out of Banderas Bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Occidental sits on Nuevo Vallarta's long beach on the Riviera Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, about 25 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. The beach (6.5) and location (8.7) are solid, though food (6.5), pool (6), and atmosphere (6.5) are its softer marks, more middle-of-the-road than standout. It's a family resort with an adult pool section for couples. Its proximity to Vallarta Adventures' excursion operations makes it a convenient base for zip-lining and dolphin encounters booked off-site. November through April is the dry season for beach days and boat trips.`,
  },
  'decameron-los-cocos-guayabitos': {
    activities: `Decameron Los Cocos rounds out the chain's cluster of budget all-inclusives in Rincón de Guayabitos, with a kids' club, tennis, adult pool, and fishing available on-site alongside the beach and buffet. This sheltered bay suits families with young children, and it's a base for exploring nearby coastal islets, sportfishing, and winter whale sightings further offshore.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Decameron sits in Rincón de Guayabitos, roughly 90 minutes north of Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport on a quieter part of the Nayarit coast. It scores lower than its Guayabitos siblings on several marks — rooms (7.4) and atmosphere (5.8) are soft — while the beach (6.8) and value (8.4) hold up better. As a budget, no-frills all-inclusive it suits families prioritizing cost and a calm beach town over resort-level polish. Guayabitos itself is a low-key alternative to the busier Nuevo Vallarta corridor. Winter is the driest, calmest season for this stretch of coast.`,
  },
  'melia-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Meliá Puerto Vallarta sits in the Marina Vallarta golf community, with discounted access to the adjacent 18-hole course, an on-site mini-golf, archery, and yoga classes alongside its pools and a kids' club for younger children. Tennis and a nightclub round out the list. The marina's restaurants are a short walk, and the resort also arranges Los Arcos snorkeling and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Meliá sits in Marina Vallarta, Puerto Vallarta's golf-and-yacht district on the Jalisco side of the bay, a short drive from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Location (8.3) is decent, but ratings run softer elsewhere — an 8.2 overall with rooms (7.8) and beach (5) among the weaker marks, honestly reflecting a more dated property and the marina's narrower beach compared with open coastline further north. It's a family resort with golf and archery among its more distinctive offerings. Book it for the marina setting and golf access rather than for beachfront. November through April is the driest season for exploring the area.`,
  },
  'barcelo-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Barceló Puerto Vallarta sits in Mismaloya cove, the filming location of Night of the Iguana, with a waterpark-style pool, slides, and arcade for kids, plus a dive program and watersports rentals off the beach. Los Arcos marine park, prime for snorkeling, is a short boat ride away, and the resort also books Sierra Madre canopy tours and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Barceló sits in Mismaloya, the cove south of downtown Puerto Vallarta made famous by the 1964 film Night of the Iguana, about 30 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Rooms (8.6) and cleanliness (8.7) are solid; food (6.8) sits closer to average for the brand. The beach, at 6, benefits from Mismaloya's sheltered cove setting compared with more exposed hotel-zone beaches. It's a family resort with a full kids' waterpark. Los Arcos, one of the region's best snorkel sites, is just offshore. November through April is the dry season for water activities.`,
  },
  'paradise-village-beach-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Paradise Village is a large, marina-adjacent complex in Nuevo Nayarit with its own on-site golf course, tennis, a kids' club, and a European-style village of shops and restaurants alongside its pools. Vallarta Adventures' excursion base and Flamingos Golf Club are both close by, and the resort books Marietas Islands boat trips and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Paradise Village sits in Nuevo Nayarit on the Riviera Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, roughly 30 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. The beach (6.8) and location (8.5) hold up well; food (6.9) is more middling. Its scale — an on-site golf course, marina, and shopping village — sets it apart from smaller nearby properties, though its price level is more moderate than some Nuevo Vallarta luxury resorts. It's a family property well suited to longer stays where guests want on-site variety. November through April is the dry season and prime whale-watching window offshore.`,
  },
  'hotel-friendly-fun-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Friendly Fun Vallarta is a smaller, family-run oceanfront hotel near La Isla shopping district, with three pools, a kids' club, gym, and spa rather than extensive resort facilities. Theme nights and beach activities fill the evenings. Its location near downtown Puerto Vallarta puts the Malecón boardwalk within reach, and Los Arcos snorkeling and December–March whale-watching trips are common excursions booked from here.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This hotel sits on the beach near Puerto Vallarta's La Isla district, a few minutes from downtown and Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Location (8.5) and service (8.6) are its stronger marks, reflecting the family-owned operation's personalized approach; food (6.3) and sleep quality (7.9) are more modest, in line with its simpler, mid-tier positioning. It suits families wanting an oceanfront base close to downtown over a large resort complex. The hotel's smaller scale and 24-hour all-inclusive format make it a straightforward, less programmed alternative to the bigger hotel-zone properties. Winter and spring bring the driest weather to the bay.`,
  },
  'costa-sur-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Costa Sur sits on Puerto Vallarta's south shore along Highway 200, with a private beach and lagoon suited to kayaking, paddleboarding, and snorkeling rather than a large pool complex. It's a simpler, lower-key property than its hotel-zone counterparts. From here, guests reach Los Arcos and Mismaloya for further snorkeling, and book Sierra Madre canopy tours and December–March whale-watching trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Costa Sur sits south of downtown Puerto Vallarta on Highway 200, on the Jalisco side of the bay, about 25 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. It's priced lower than most nearby resorts, and the ratings reflect that positioning — an 8.4 overall with the beach, at 4.3, the weakest mark, since the coastline here is more lagoon-and-rock than open sand. Rooms and food sit in the mid-to-high 6s and 7s, modest but workable. It suits budget-conscious travelers prioritizing the south-shore setting and value over resort polish. November through April is the driest season for the water activities on offer here.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-vallarta': {
    activities: `Hotel Riu Vallarta, the family counterpart to nearby Riu Palace Pacífico, offers the chain's standard large buffet and à la carte rotation with reservation-free dining, set on a well-regarded stretch of Nuevo Nayarit beach. Evening entertainment runs nightly. Off-site, Marietas Islands boat trips, Punta de Mita's surf breaks, and December–March whale-watching excursions are typical outings from this part of Riviera Nayarit.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Vallarta sits in Nuevo Nayarit on the Riviera Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, roughly 25 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. The beach, at 6.8, is a genuine strength here, better than many Puerto Vallarta city properties, while food (6.4) and atmosphere (6.5) run more average, standard for the high-volume Riu format. It's a family resort, with adults-only sister property Riu Palace Pacífico next door for couples wanting a childfree stay. Book it for the beach and reliable Riu formula rather than culinary standout. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'samba-vallarta': {
    activities: `Samba Vallarta is a mid-size, family-run property on Flamingos beach with three interconnected pools, non-motorized watersports like kayaks and boogie boards, a playground, and nightly theme entertainment. Its beachfront position on this stretch of Riviera Nayarit sand is a genuine draw. Nearby, guests book Marietas Islands boat trips, Punta de Mita surf lessons, and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Samba Vallarta sits on Flamingos beach in Riviera Nayarit, about eight miles from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. The beach, at 6.8, is one of its better marks, while food (6.2) and sleep quality (8.1) sit closer to average for its budget-to-moderate price tier. With around 180 rooms, it's smaller and simpler than the mega-resorts nearby, which keeps rates lower but means less extensive dining and entertainment. It's a family property with a straightforward, beach-first appeal. Winter and spring bring the driest weather and the best whale-watching conditions offshore.`,
  },
  'dreams-bahia-mita-surf-and-spa-resort': {
    activities: `Dreams Bahía Mita, the family-inclusive sibling to Secrets Bahía Mita at Punta de Mita, offers a kids' club for younger children, spa, and evening entertainment with restaurants that skip reservations. The point breaks just offshore make this a natural base for surf lessons, and the resort also books Marietas Islands boat trips and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Dreams resort sits at Punta de Mita, the surf point at the north end of Banderas Bay in Riviera Nayarit, about 45 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Cleanliness (9.2) and room quality (9) are strong; the beach, at 4.8, is honestly the weakest mark, since Punta de Mita's shoreline here favors surf breaks and rocky points over swimming sand. It's a family-oriented, unlimited-luxury resort, with adults-only sister Secrets Bahía Mita next door for couples. Book it for the surf culture and Marietas Islands access rather than classic beach swimming. Winter is the dry season and a strong surf shoulder season.`,
  },
  'hacienda-buenaventura-hotel-and-mexican-charm': {
    activities: `Hacienda Buenaventura leans into a colonial Mexican theme in its architecture and décor, set in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone with straightforward pool and beachfront days rather than extensive programming. Its location keeps the Malecón and Zona Romántica within easy reach for dining and nightlife, and the hotel arranges Los Arcos snorkeling and December–March whale-watching trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This hotel sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, close to Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport and downtown. Value (8.6) and service (8.6) are decent for the price point; the beach, at 3, is genuinely the weakest mark in this stretch — narrow and exposed compared with the wider sand north of the bay. Its Mexican-hacienda styling is a real, if modest, point of character among more generic hotel-zone towers. It's a family property best booked for its location and value rather than beachfront. November through April brings the driest, most comfortable weather.`,
  },
  'fiesta-americana-riviera-nayarit': {
    activities: `Fiesta Americana Riviera Nayarit sits in Nuevo Vallarta with straightforward pool, beach, and dining days built around the brand's standard all-inclusive format rather than an extensive activity roster. Its beach here is a genuine asset. Off-site, guests book Marietas Islands boat trips, Sierra Madre canopy tours, and December–March whale-watching excursions typical of this stretch of Riviera Nayarit.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Fiesta Americana sits in Nuevo Vallarta on the Riviera Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, about 30 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. The beach, at 6.8, is one of its better marks, on par with the area's stronger properties; value (8), pool (6.5), and atmosphere (6.8) sit more toward the middle. It's a family resort without extensive kids' programming listed, so it suits travelers who want a beach-first stay over heavy activity scheduling. Book it for the Nuevo Vallarta beach and brand reliability. November through April is the dry season and prime whale-watching window.`,
  },
  'krystal-grand-nuevo-vallarta': {
    activities: `Krystal Grand Nuevo Vallarta sits on one of the corridor's better beaches, with straightforward pool and beachfront days and the chain's standard dining rotation. Guests here also use it as a base for Vallarta Adventures excursions nearby, Marietas Islands boat trips, and December–March whale-watching outings typical of this part of Banderas Bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Krystal Grand sits in Nuevo Vallarta on the Riviera Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, roughly 25 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport, distinct from its same-named sibling in downtown Puerto Vallarta. The beach, at 6.8, is genuinely one of the better marks in the Krystal portfolio here, while food (6.4) and atmosphere (6.2) are more average. It's a family resort, priced as a solid mid-tier option rather than a luxury one. Consider it for the beach and location over dining ambition. November through April is the dry season for beach days and boat excursions.`,
  },
  'canto-del-sol-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Canto del Sol is a long-running, mid-range hotel-zone property with a beachfront pool and the basics of an all-inclusive stay rather than an extensive activity list. Its location keeps the Malecón and Zona Romántica an easy trip away. Guests here also book Los Arcos snorkeling, Sierra Madre canopy tours, and December–March whale-watching excursions from the nearby marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Canto del Sol sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, close to Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Location (8.3) and value (8.1) hold up reasonably; the beach, at 5.5, and pool, at 5.6, are softer marks, reflecting an older, simpler property compared with newer hotel-zone builds. It's a family resort priced accessibly rather than aimed at luxury travelers. Book it for the central location and value rather than for standout facilities. November through April is the dry season, the easiest stretch for exploring downtown on foot.`,
  },
  'krystal-grand-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Krystal Grand Puerto Vallarta is split into a family-facing Resort side with direct beach access and a separate adults-only Hacienda section built around a quieter pool. Both share the chain's standard buffet and entertainment. The hotel zone location puts the Malecón and cruise terminal close by, and the resort arranges Los Arcos snorkeling and December–March whale-watching trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Krystal Grand sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, near the cruise terminal and about 10 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Cleanliness (8.4) and value (7.9) are typical for the tier; food (6.4) and pool (6) run more modest. Its dual-section format — beachfront family rooms versus the adults-only Hacienda wing without ocean views — means the experience varies noticeably depending on which side you book. It's worth confirming which section applies before booking. November through April is the dry season for downtown sightseeing.`,
  },
  'crown-paradise-golden-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Crown Paradise Golden is the adults-only section of the wider Crown Paradise complex in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone, with a quieter pool scene than the family side next door. The Malecón and Zona Romántica are a short trip for dining and nightlife, and the resort books Los Arcos snorkeling trips and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This property sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, close to Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Ratings run modest across the board, with an 8.1 overall, rooms at 7.5, and value at 7.7 — workable but not standout. The beach, at 5.3, is typical of the more built-up hotel-zone shoreline. As the adults-only Golden section of a larger family complex, it suits couples wanting quiet without leaving the shared amenities behind. Budget expectations accordingly at this price tier. November through April is the driest, most comfortable season.`,
  },
  'grand-decameron-complex-bucerias': {
    activities: `Grand Decameron Complex sits in Bucerías, the fishing-village-turned-resort-town known for its Wednesday art walk and long beach. Days here center on the beach and buffet rather than extensive facilities. Guests use the town's galleries and restaurants for evenings out, and book Marietas Islands boat trips, Sierra Madre canopy tours, and December–March whale-watching excursions from nearby Riviera Nayarit marinas.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Decameron sits in Bucerías, a former fishing village on the Riviera Nayarit coast known for its Wednesday evening art walk, about 30 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. The beach (6.3) and value (8.2) are decent; rooms (7.3) and atmosphere (6.2) are softer, reflecting a budget-tier, no-frills all-inclusive format. It's a family property that works best for travelers prioritizing Bucerías' laid-back town character and lower price over resort-level polish. Book it for the beach and the town's gallery scene rather than facilities. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-jalisco': {
    activities: `Despite its name, Hotel Riu Jalisco actually sits on Flamingos beach in Nuevo Vallarta, on the Riviera Nayarit side of the bay, with the chain's standard buffet and reservation-free dining and a waterpark section for younger kids. It shares its stretch of beach and evening entertainment with neighboring Riu properties. Off-site, guests book Marietas Islands boat trips and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Jalisco sits in Nuevo Vallarta on the Riviera Nayarit side of Banderas Bay, about 10 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport — the Jalisco in its name is a brand holdover, not its actual location. The beach, at 6.5, is solid; food (6.3) and pool (6) are more average, standard for the high-volume Riu format. It's a family resort within walking distance of sister Riu properties along the same beach. Book it for the reliable Riu formula and beach access rather than culinary ambition. November through April is the dry season for beach days.`,
  },
  'vamar-vallarta-marina-and-beach-resort': {
    activities: `Vamar Vallarta sits in Marina Vallarta, the golf-and-yacht district, with straightforward pool and beach days rather than an extensive activity list. The marina's restaurants and galleries are a short walk, and the adjacent golf course is available for guests. From here, Los Arcos snorkeling, Marietas Islands boat trips, and December–March whale-watching excursions are common day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Vamar Vallarta sits in Marina Vallarta on the Jalisco side of Banderas Bay, about five minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport and 20 minutes from the Malecón. Ratings sit on the softer side across categories — an 8.1 overall with the beach at 4.3 and pool at 5.1 among the weaker marks, reflecting an older, budget-tier property in a marina setting rather than open beachfront. It's a family resort best suited to travelers prioritizing the marina location and price over resort polish. November through April is the dry season for exploring the marina district and beyond.`,
  },
  'grand-matlali-riviera-nayarit': {
    activities: `Grand Matlali is a hillside suites-and-villas property above La Cruz de Huanacaxtle, set back from the water with gardens, a pool, and a fitness center rather than a beachfront scene; a private beach area sits roughly a mile and a half away. Guests use La Cruz's marina and Sunday organic market for outings, and book sportfishing charters, Marietas Islands boat trips, and December–March whale-watching excursions from the nearby marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Grand Matlali sits on a hillside above La Cruz de Huanacaxtle, the marina town on the Riviera Nayarit coast, about 40 minutes from Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. The beach score here, at 2, is honestly the lowest in this stretch of coast — the property's private beach access sits over a mile from the hillside suites, so this is not a beachfront stay. Rooms (8.3) and cleanliness (8.4) hold up well, in keeping with its villa-and-suite format. Book it for the hillside setting, gardens, and La Cruz's marina and Sunday market rather than for swimming. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'sunscape-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Sunscape Puerto Vallarta, AMResorts' family-friendly sibling to nearby Secrets and Dreams properties, offers straightforward pool and beachfront days in the hotel zone with the brand's standard all-inclusive format. The Malecón and Zona Romántica are a short trip for dining out, and the resort books Los Arcos snorkeling and December–March whale-watching excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Sunscape sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, close to Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport. Location (8.3) is solid; the beach, at 5.3, and rooms, at 7.7, are more modest, in line with its positioning as the value-oriented sibling to AMResorts' upscale Secrets and Dreams brands nearby. It's a family resort without extensive kids' programming listed, so expect a simpler, lower-key stay than the area's bigger family resorts. Book it for the price point and hotel-zone location. November through April brings the driest, most comfortable weather.`,
  },
  'hotel-krystal-puerto-vallarta': {
    activities: `Hotel Krystal Puerto Vallarta sits beside its larger Krystal Grand sibling in the hotel zone but operates independently, with simpler pool and beachfront days rather than extensive facilities. The Malecón and Zona Romántica are a short trip for evenings out. Guests also book Los Arcos snorkeling, Sierra Madre canopy tours, and December–March whale-watching excursions from the nearby marina.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This hotel sits in Puerto Vallarta's hotel zone on the Jalisco side of the bay, close to Licenciado Gustavo Díaz Ordaz International Airport, adjacent to but run separately from Krystal Grand Puerto Vallarta. Ratings run on the lower side here — a 7.8 overall with rooms (7.1), value (7.1), and service (7.7) among the softer marks, reflecting its older, budget positioning. The beach, at 5.3, is average for the hotel zone. It's a family property best suited to travelers prioritizing price and hotel-zone location over facilities. November through April is the dry season for exploring nearby downtown.`,
  },
}
